# AI Safety in Nonprofit HR

*For small HR shops, nonprofit boards, and organizations without a dedicated AI governance function.*

**Audience:** Nonprofit HR leaders, small HR shops, board members with HR oversight

*Richard Porter · Part of the AI Safety in HR Framework · 2026*

-----

> **Who This Is For**
> You are running HR for a nonprofit or small organization where “the HR function” may be one person — or a board committee. You are being asked to evaluate or deploy AI tools with limited legal support, limited budget, and very real exposure. This toolkit is written for that reality.

-----

## Why Nonprofits Face a Different Risk Profile

Large enterprises have legal teams, compliance departments, and HR technology governance functions reviewing these decisions. Nonprofits typically have none of these. What nonprofits do have — in common with any employer — is full exposure to the same legal consequences when AI-assisted HR decisions go wrong.

**Three risks specific to nonprofit HR:**

**1. No internal check.** The person evaluating the AI tool is often the same person who will use it. There is no second set of eyes between evaluation and deployment.

**2. Volunteer and staff blur.** The line between volunteer and employee is already a compliance risk. AI tools that process both without distinguishing them amplify it. An AI that generates a termination recommendation for what it classifies as an “employee” may be acting on someone who is legally a volunteer — or vice versa.

**3. Resource pressure.** Nonprofits are particularly vulnerable to AI tools marketed as cost-saving substitutes for HR staff — which tend to carry the highest legal risk. The cheapest AI HR tool is usually the one with the least governance infrastructure.

